10. Heat map analysis

Heat map analysis is mainly used to present a large set of data in color. This kind of plot can not be produced by other method.

suppose u have a data of 500x 500 how should you show them. Heat map

in the diamonds dataset, it reports exactly 53940 observations (piece of diamonds),lets heat map their dimentions (x,y,z columns).

2 things u need to think about when doing heatmap

turning you data into matrix log the data if there is much variability between reads

head(iris)
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 2          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2  setosa
## 4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2  setosa
## 5          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4  setosa

i need to remove the last column (species). I’ll do that using select code in plyr and dplyr packages

data <- select(iris,-Species)# - means 'make a new data called 'data' from iris dataset without species column
head(data)
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2
## 2          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2
## 3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2
## 4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2
## 5          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2
## 6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4

check what kind of data i have

class(data)# tells u what class of data ; hereit is data.frame
## [1] "data.frame"

Turn it into matrix

data_matrix <- as.matrix(data)

I will generate the heat map

data_heatmap <-heatmap(data_matrix, Rowv=NA, Colv=NA, col =heat.colors(256), scale="column", margins=c(5,10))

the color increase in intensity with value increase.

Lets do more sophisticated heatmap. I will use another package called gplots, also we need RColorBrewer package to play with the colors

heatmap.2(data_matrix, col=redgreen(75), scale="row", key=T, keysize=1.5,density.info="none", trace="none",cexCol=0.9, labRow=NA)

this code generates 2 more peices of information, one is the z score, where it changes the value into another score within a scale from -1 to 1. so, observations close to 1 is high, while those near to -1 are low read observations. another thing, it cluster both rows and columns based on similarity

head(data_matrix,n=5)# highest reads in septal length and lowest in petal width
##      Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
## [1,]          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2
## [2,]          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2
## [3,]          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2
## [4,]          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2
## [5,]          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2

its important to tell R if you want to score based on row or column. color of each pixel is compared to row or column?. in general u need to do it by row “as each row is an observation”

lets see if we changed scoring to col

heatmap.2(data_matrix, col=redgreen(75), scale="col", key=T, keysize=1.5,density.info="none", trace="none",cexCol=0.9, labRow=NA)

additional information could be added (histogram) in the key, lets see how

heatmap.2(data_matrix,col=greenred(75),scale="col")

note that here the color is reversed, u can always check the key

Professional plotting tip

Heat map generate a big plot that might contain observations with no significant changes. we can refine the matrix by telling R to plot most variable observations “in most cases most significant”. in many cases this might plot more clear “less crowded” images.

head(data_matrix)
##      Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
## [1,]          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2
## [2,]          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2
## [3,]          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2
## [4,]          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2
## [5,]          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2
## [6,]          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4
str(data_matrix)# note that data matrix is 150 obs
##  num [1:150, 1:4] 5.1 4.9 4.7 4.6 5 5.4 4.6 5 4.4 4.9 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : NULL
##   ..$ : chr [1:4] "Sepal.Length" "Sepal.Width" "Petal.Length" "Petal.Width"

now follow me

var <- apply(data_matrix,1,var) #calculate variance in the data. require plyr and dplyr packages. 
mostvariable <- data_matrix[var>quantile(var,0.75),]# telling R to make a new matrix called most varibale by selecting row that is above 75Th percentile. This means top 25% [remember box plot explanation?]
str(mostvariable)# R selected 38 observations from the original 150. smart:)
##  num [1:38, 1:4] 5.4 5.4 5.8 5.7 5.4 5.7 5.4 5.2 5.2 5.4 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : NULL
##   ..$ : chr [1:4] "Sepal.Length" "Sepal.Width" "Petal.Length" "Petal.Width"

lets heatmap them

heatmap.2(mostvariable,col=greenred(75),scale="col")

I dont like the color, lets change it

heatmap.2(mostvariable,col=redblue(75),scale="col")

#reset graphical device
dev.off()
## null device 
##           1

remember, the number after color [redblue(75)] is the palette percision. try 20 and 200 for example. it affects histogram (binwidth)

you can change the text angle, change keysize,remove dendrogram,remove trace “indicator lines within pixels”, change text size for row and col by adding these extensions.

try it by yourself

heatmap.2(mostvariable,col=redblue(75),scale=“col”,srtCol=45,keysize=1,dendrogram=“none”, trace=“none”,cexRow=1.5,cexCol=1.5)

my graph

When working with R , you need to think about your data arrangement before coding for graphics.

*** lets import iris dataset again***

*** we need to make another table includes the mean , SD, SEM for the data based on species. At first, i will use only Sepal.Length column***

*** i will use ddply function “check earlier topic about error bars in part 1”***

barsummary_septal <- ddply(iris, c("Species"), summarise,mvalue = mean(Sepal.Length, na.rm=TRUE),medvalue=median(Sepal.Length, na.rm=TRUE), sd = sd(Sepal.Length, na.rm=TRUE),n = sum(!is.na(Sepal.Length)),se = sd/sqrt(n))
barsummary_septal
##      Species mvalue medvalue        sd  n         se
## 1     setosa  5.006      5.0 0.3524897 50 0.04984957
## 2 versicolor  5.936      5.9 0.5161711 50 0.07299762
## 3  virginica  6.588      6.5 0.6358796 50 0.08992695

Now , i can plot the graph

ggplot(barsummary_septal, aes(x=Species, y=mvalue)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(x="Species", y="Sepal.Length")

*** Yes, its Ugly***

In previous initial graph, i created a summary table for “spetal.length” that includes, mean, median, number of observation and standard error of mean. I will use the SD or SEM for plotting error bars later. but now , i want to resummarize the barsummary data to include all other flower columns.

###here is the steps

  1. changing the format of the table to long using melt function (reshape 2 package) based on species
melted <- melt(iris, id.vars=c("Species"))

###check the new table shape

head(melted)

## 6  setosa Sepal.Length   5.4
tail(melted)

## 596 virginica Petal.Width   2.3
## 597 virginica Petal.Width   1.9
## 598 virginica Petal.Width   2.0
## 599 virginica Petal.Width   2.3
## 600 virginica Petal.Width   1.8

2. Now, i will resummarize the data based on *** species and variable***

barsummary_all <- ddply(melted, c("Species","variable"), summarise,mvalue = mean(value, na.rm=TRUE),medvalue=median(value, na.rm=TRUE), sd = sd(value, na.rm=TRUE),n = sum(!is.na(value)),se = sd/sqrt(n))

###Now, we are ready

ggplot(barsummary_all, aes(x=variable, y=mvalue,fill=Species)) + geom_bar(position="dodge",color="black",stat="identity") + labs(x="flower parts", y="value")

more better,lets add the error bars “check error bar previously discussed”. I can use SD or SEM from the table. Here i will use SD.

ggplot(barsummary_all, aes(x=variable, y=mvalue,fill=Species)) + geom_bar(position="dodge",color="black",stat="identity") + labs(x="flower parts", y="Value")+geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mvalue-sd,ymax=mvalue+sd),position=position_dodge(0.9), width=.2)

adding some suger to the graph

ggplot(barsummary_all, aes(x=variable, y=mvalue,fill=Species)) + geom_bar(position="dodge",color="black",stat="identity") + labs(x="Flower parts", y="Value")+geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mvalue-sd,ymax=mvalue+sd),position=position_dodge(0.9), width=.2)+ theme_bw()+theme(text = element_text(size=15, face="bold", colour="black"),axis.text.x = element_text(vjust=2))+scale_fill_brewer(palette="Pastel1")

note that you can always change the color as you like from RColorBrewer package. Make sure you loaded the package “library(RColorBrewer)”.

display.brewer.all() # to see the palettes

you can reorder the data viewing based on the value ascendingly or descendingly

ascendingly

ggplot(barsummary_all, aes(x=reorder(variable,mvalue), y=mvalue,fill=Species)) + geom_bar(position="dodge",color="black",stat="identity") + labs(x="Flower parts", y="Value")+geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mvalue-sd,ymax=mvalue+sd),position=position_dodge(0.9), width=.2)+ theme_bw()+theme(text = element_text(size=15, face="bold", colour="black"),axis.text.x = element_text(vjust=2))+scale_fill_brewer(palette="Pastel1")

descendingly

ggplot(barsummary_all, aes(x=reorder(variable,-mvalue), y=mvalue,fill=Species)) + geom_bar(position="dodge",color="black",stat="identity") + labs(x="Flower parts", y="Value")+geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mvalue-sd,ymax=mvalue+sd),position=position_dodge(0.9), width=.2)+ theme_bw()+theme(text = element_text(size=15, face="bold", colour="black"),axis.text.x = element_text(vjust=2))+scale_fill_brewer(palette="Pastel1")

you can control almost anything in the graph, for example the width of the column

ggplot(barsummary_all, aes(x=reorder(variable,-mvalue), y=mvalue,fill=Species)) + geom_bar(position="dodge",color="black",stat="identity",width=0.5) + labs(x="Flower parts", y="Value")+geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mvalue-sd,ymax=mvalue+sd),position=position_dodge(0.35), width=.5)+ theme_bw()+theme(text = element_text(size=15, face="bold", colour="black"),axis.text.x = element_text(vjust=2))+scale_fill_brewer(palette="Pastel1")

but you will need also to tweak the error bar dimensions

ggplot(barsummary_all, aes(x=reorder(variable,-mvalue), y=mvalue,fill=Species)) + geom_bar(position="dodge",color="black",stat="identity",width=0.5) + labs(x="Flower parts", y="Value")+geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mvalue-sd,ymax=mvalue+sd),position=position_dodge(0.5), width=.25)+ theme_bw()+theme(text = element_text(size=15, face="bold", colour="black"),axis.text.x = element_text(vjust=2))+scale_fill_brewer(palette="Pastel1")

12. Stacked bar plot

Stacked bar plot will have the same approach as bar plot. the only difference that i will remove error bar info from the code and i will remove also position =“dodge” [this one tells R to plot side by side]. comapre between the following code and the earlier one

ggplot(barsummary_all, aes(x=reorder(variable,-mvalue), y=mvalue,fill=Species)) + geom_bar(color="black",stat="identity",width=0.5) + labs(x="Flower parts", y="Value")+ theme_bw()+theme(text = element_text(size=15, face="bold", colour="black"),axis.text.x = element_text(vjust=2))+scale_fill_brewer(palette="Pastel1")

mutate function in ddplyr adds new column to existing table by applying some operations.

barsummary_all2 <- grouped %>% mutate(percentage=mvalue/sum(mvalue)*100) # telling R to generate a new data called barsummary_all2 by reading grouped data and adding a new column called percentage that fullfills the equation; mvalue devided by the sum (of each group) then *100 to get percentage.

14. Scatter plot matrix

Scatter plot matrix is a matrix of several scatter plots. Lets see how it looks like

lets work on mtcars dataset

head(mtcars) # datasets package
##                    mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Mazda RX4         21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.620 16.46  0  1    4    4
## Mazda RX4 Wag     21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.875 17.02  0  1    4    4
## Datsun 710        22.8   4  108  93 3.85 2.320 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Hornet 4 Drive    21.4   6  258 110 3.08 3.215 19.44  1  0    3    1
## Hornet Sportabout 18.7   8  360 175 3.15 3.440 17.02  0  0    3    2
## Valiant           18.1   6  225 105 2.76 3.460 20.22  1  0    3    1

straight forward and easiest scatter plot using plot function. This function in the core package of R

plot(mtcars)

however, in some cases, we don’t need to plot all variables, lets select only from disp column to qsec. To do so, i will use select function (plyr package). i will name the new subset data as cars.

cars <- mtcars %>% select(disp,hp,drat,wt,qsec)# cars <- read mtcars, and select from it these columns

Now, lets do our graph

plot(cars)

there is more informative scatter matrix plot function in car package, lets see how it works.

scatterplotMatrix(cars, spread=FALSE, lty.smooth=2, main="cars scatter matrix plot")

As you see, this plot is very useful in case of bivariate correlation to examine the relationship among variables (2 or more).

This graph includes liner and smoothed fit and marginal distributions (Kernel density and rug plots).

Hint: to examine the correlation

cor(cars) # default is pearson, to use kendall or spearman just add method="spearman"
##            disp         hp        drat         wt        qsec

# Im giving another coarse for correlation and regression in a more detailed approach

For me, i like the function ggpairs in (GGally package), lets see why.

ggpairs(cars)

here it combines scatter plot, kernel density and correlation together.
